  "prompt": "Isn't money laundering illegal?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal in virtually all jurisdictions around the world. Money laundering is the process of making illegally obtained money (such as from drug trafficking, corruption, or fraud) appear legitimate by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. The goal is to obscure the original source of the funds and make them seem like they came from legal activities.\n\n### Key Points:\n1. **Legality**: Money laundering is a criminal offense under both national and international laws.\n2. **Purpose**: It is typically done to evade taxes, hide criminal activity, or finance further illegal operations.\n3. **Methods**: Common methods include using shell companies, offshore accounts, real estate transactions, or cryptocurrency to \"clean\" the money.\n4. **Consequences**: Penalties for money laundering can include hefty fines, asset seizures, and imprisonment. Banks and financial institutions are also required to report suspicious activities to authorities under anti-money laundering (AML) regulations.\n\nGovernments and international organizations, such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), work to combat money laundering by implementing strict regulations and monitoring financial systems.",
